a(S'Dementia[edit]'
p8582
g2
tp8583
a(S"Alzheimer's disease and other types of dementia are among the disorders "
p8584
g2
tp8585
a(S'most commonly treated with music therapy. Like many of the other disorders '
p8586
g2
tp8587
a(S'mentioned, some of the most common significant effects are seen in social '
p8588
g2
tp8589
a(S'behaviors, leading to improvements in interaction, conversation, and other '
p8590
g2
tp8591
a(S'such skills. A meta-study of over 330 subjects showed music therapy '
p8592
g2
tp8593
a(S'produces highly significant improvements to social behaviors, overt '
p8594
g2
tp8595
a(S'behaviors like wandering and restlessness, reductions in agitated behaviors, '
p8596
g2
tp8597
a(S'and improvements to cognitive defects, measured with reality orientation and '
p8598
g2
tp8599
a(S'face recognition tests.[78] As with many studies of MT s effectiveness, these '
p8600
g2
tp8601
a(S"positive effects on Alzheimer's and other dementias are not homogeneous "
p8602
g2
tp8603
a(S'among all studies. The effectiveness of the treatment seems to be strongly '
p8604
g2
tp8605
a(S'dependent on the patient, the quality and length of treatment, and other '
p8606
g2
tp8607
a(S'similar factors.[79]'
p8608
g2
tp8609
a(g6
g2
tp8610
a(S'Another meta-study examined the proposed neurological mechanisms '
p8611
g2
tp8612
a(S'behind music therapy s effects on these patients. Many authors suspect that '
p8613
g2
tp8614
a(S'music has a soothing effect on the patient by affecting how noise is '
p8615
g2
tp8616
a(S'perceived: music renders noise familiar, or buffers the patient from '
p8617
g2
tp8618
a(S'overwhelming or extraneous noise in their environment. Others suggest that '
p8619
g2
tp8620
a(S'music serves as a sort of mediator for social interactions, providing a vessel '
p8621
g2
tp8622
a(S'through which to interact with others without requiring much cognitive load.'
p8623
g2
tp8624
a(S'[79] Because Music has the ability to access multiple parts of the brain, '
p8625
g2
tp8626
a(S'music therapy is highly effective in providing therapeutic support for '
p8627
g2
tp8628
a(S'individuals with all types of dementia. Research indicates that the sections of '
p8629
g2
tp8630
a(S'the brain weakened by dementia can be supported and in some cases '
p8631
g2
tp8632
a(S'strengthened by other areas of the brain through musical activities. Musical '
p8633
g2
tp8634
a(S'ability and awareness is also one of the last functions to be compromised in '
p8635
g2
tp8636
a(S'an individual with dementia, which makes it an especially effective '
p8637
g2
tp8638
a(S'intervention, even in people with very late stage forms of the disease.[80] '
p8639
g2
tp8640
a(S'Music therapy is more than simply listening to or playing music. Through the '
p8641
g2
tp8642
a(S'use of evidence based interventions and clinical assessments, a music '
p8643
g2
tp8644
a(S'therapist works to improve the lives and abilities of individuals. These '
p8645
g2
tp8646
a(S'interventions can decrease anxiety, improve speech and self- expression, '
p8647
g2
tp8648
a(S'and a decrease in negative behaviors and isolation which are commonly '
p8649
g2
tp8650
a(S'found in individuals with dementia.[81] Common negative behaviors that '
p8651
g2
tp8652
a(S'correspond with dementia are depression and agitation. According to Dr. '
p8653
g2
tp8654
a(S'Mary S. Mittelman, the director of psychosocial research at Langone Medical '
p8655
g2
tp8656
a(S'Center, music therapy helped to decrease both of these negative '
p8657
g2
tp8658
a(S'substantially. The reason for this is because in the brain, the parts '
p8659
g2
tp8660
a(S'corresponding to music are preserved even through the effects of dementia. '
p8661
g2
tp8662
a(S'Due to these being preserved, residents who live their lives in a blur, find '
p8663
g2
tp8664
a(S'some clarity and familiarity through music. Thus creating lower levels of '
p8665
g2
tp8666
a(S'stress and agitation.[82]'
