tp8707
a(S'Melodic intonation therapy (MIT) is a commonly used method of treating '
p8708
g2
tp8709
a(S'aphasias, particularly those involving speech deficits (as opposed to reading '
p8710
g2
tp8711
a(S'or writing). MIT is a multi-stage treatment that involves committing words and '
p8712
g2
tp8713
a(S'speech rhythm to memory by incorporating them into song. The musical and '
p8714
g2
tp8715
a(S'rhythmic aspects are then separated from the speech and phased out, until '
p8716
g2
tp8717
a(S'the patient can speak normally. This method has slight variations between '
p8718
g2
tp8719
a(S'adult patients and child patients, but both follow the same basic structure.'
p8720
g2
tp8721
a(g6
g2
tp8722
a(S'While MIT is a commonly used therapy, research supporting its effectiveness '
p8723
g2
tp8724
a(S'is lacking. Some recent research suggests that the therapy s efficacy may '
p8725
g2
tp8726
a(S'stem more from the rhythmic components of the treatment rather than the '
p8727
g2
tp8728
a(S'melodic aspects.[85]'
