a(S"On February 1, 2010, Intel and Micron announced that they were gearing up for production of NAND flash memory using a new 25-nanometer process.[97] In March of that same year, Intel entered the budget SSD segment with its X25-V drives with an initial capacity of 40GB.[98] The SSD 310, Intel's first mSATA drive was released on December 2010, providing X25-M G2 performance in a much smaller package.[99][100]"
