a(S'In the 1770s Pierre Jaquet Droz, a Swiss watchmaker, built a mechanical doll (automata) that could write holding a quill pen. By switching the number and order of its internal wheels different letters, and hence different messages, could be produced. In effect, it could be mechanically "programmed" to read instructions. Along with two other complex machines, the doll is at the Mus e d\'Art et d\'Histoire of Neuch tel, Switzerland, and still operates.[14]'
