tp24158
a(S'During World War II, the British at Bletchley Park achieved a number of successes at breaking encrypted German military communications. The German encryption machine, Enigma, was first attacked with the help of the electro mechanical bombes. To crack the more sophisticated German Lorenz SZ 40/42 machine, used for high level Army communications, Max Newman and his colleagues commissioned Flowers to build the Colossus.[31] He spent eleven months from early February 1943 designing and building the first Colossus.[32] After a functional test in December 1943, Colossus was shipped to Bletchley Park, where it was delivered on 18 January 1944[33] and attacked its first message on 5 February.[31]'
