a(S'By implementation[edit]'
p25934
g19085
tp25935
a(S'One way to classify algorithms is by implementation means.'
p25936
g19085
tp25937
a(g6
g19085
tp25938
a(S'Recursion'
p25939
g19085
tp25940
a(S'A recursive algorithm is one that invokes (makes reference to) itself repeatedly until a certain condition (also known as termination condition) matches, which is a method '
p25941
g19085
tp25942
a(S'common to functional programming. Iterative algorithms use repetitive constructs like loops and sometimes additional data structures like stacks to solve the given '
p25943
g19085
tp25944
a(S'problems. Some problems are naturally suited for one implementation or the other. For example, towers of Hanoi is well understood using recursive implementation. Every '
p25945
g19085
tp25946
a(S'recursive version has an equivalent (but possibly more or less complex) iterative version, and vice versa.'
p25947
g19085
tp25948
a(S'Logical'
p25949
g19085
tp25950
a(S'An algorithm may be viewed as controlled logical deduction. This notion may be expressed as: Algorithm = logic + control.[54] The logic component expresses the axioms '
p25951
g19085
tp25952
a(S'that may be used in the computation and the control component determines the way in which deduction is applied to the axioms. This is the basis for the logic '
p25953
g19085
tp25954
a(S'programming paradigm. In pure logic programming languages the control component is fixed and algorithms are specified by supplying only the logic component. The '
p25955
g19085
tp25956
a(S'appeal of this approach is the elegant semantics: a change in the axioms has a well defined change in the algorithm.'
p25957
g19085
tp25958
a(S'Serial, parallel or distributed'
p25959
g19085
tp25960
a(S'Algorithms are usually discussed with the assumption that computers execute one instruction of an algorithm at a time. Those computers are sometimes called serial '
p25961
g19085
tp25962
a(S'computers. An algorithm designed for such an environment is called a serial algorithm, as opposed to parallel algorithms or distributed algorithms. Parallel algorithms take '
p25963
g19085
tp25964
a(S'advantage of computer architectures where several processors can work on a problem at the same time, whereas distributed algorithms utilize multiple machines '
p25965
g19085
tp25966
a(S'connected with a network. Parallel or distributed algorithms divide the problem into more symmetrical or asymmetrical subproblems and collect the results back together. '
p25967
g19085
tp25968
a(S'The resource consumption in such algorithms is not only processor cycles on each processor but also the communication overhead between the processors. Some '
p25969
g19085
tp25970
a(S'sorting algorithms can be parallelized efficiently, but their communication overhead is expensive. Iterative algorithms are generally parallelizable. Some problems have no '
p25971
g19085
tp25972
a(S'parallel algorithms, and are called inherently serial problems.'
p25973
g19085
tp25974
a(S'Deterministic or non deterministic'
p25975
g19085
tp25976
a(S'Deterministic algorithms solve the problem with exact decision at every step of the algorithm whereas non deterministic algorithms solve problems via guessing although '
p25977
g19085
tp25978
a(S'typical guesses are made more accurate through the use of heuristics.'
p25979
g19085
tp25980
a(S'Exact or approximate'
p25981
g19085
tp25982
a(S'While many algorithms reach an exact solution, approximation algorithms seek an approximation that is close to the true solution. Approximation may use either a '
p25983
g19085
tp25984
a(S'deterministic or a random strategy. Such algorithms have practical value for many hard problems.'
p25985
g19085
tp25986
a(S'Quantum algorithm'
p25987
g19085
tp25988
a(S'They run on a realistic model of quantum computation. The term is usually used for those algorithms which seem inherently quantum, or use some essential feature of '
p25989
g19085
tp25990
a(S'quantum computation such as quantum superposition or quantum entanglement.'
p25991
g19085
tp25992
a(S'By design paradigm[edit]'
p25993
g19085
tp25994
a(S'Another way of classifying algorithms is by their design methodology or paradigm. There is a certain number of paradigms, each different from the other. Furthermore, '
p25995
g19085
tp25996
a(S'each of these categories include many different types of algorithms. Some common paradigms are:'
p25997
g19085
tp25998
a(g6
g19085
tp25999
a(S'Brute force or exhaustive search'
p26000
g19085
tp26001
a(S'This is the naive method of trying every possible solution to see which is best.[55]'
p26002
g19085
tp26003
a(S'Divide and conquer'
p26004
g19085
tp26005
a(S'A divide and conquer algorithm repeatedly reduces an instance of a problem to one or more smaller instances of the same problem (usually recursively) until the instances '
p26006
g19085
tp26007
a(S'are small enough to solve easily. One such example of divide and conquer is merge sorting. Sorting can be done on each segment of data after dividing data into '
p26008
g19085
tp26009
a(S'segments and sorting of entire data can be obtained in the conquer phase by merging the segments. A simpler variant of divide and conquer is called a decrease and '
p26010
g19085
tp26011
a(S'conquer algorithm, that solves an identical subproblem and uses the solution of this subproblem to solve the bigger problem. Divide and conquer divides the problem into '
p26012
g19085
tp26013
a(S'multiple subproblems and so the conquer stage is more complex than decrease and conquer algorithms. An example of decrease and conquer algorithm is the binary '
p26014
g19085
tp26015
a(S'search algorithm.'
p26016
g19085
tp26017
a(S'Search and enumeration'
p26018
g19085
tp26019
a(S'Many problems (such as playing chess) can be modeled as problems on graphs. A graph exploration algorithm specifies rules for moving around a graph and is useful for '
p26020
g19085
tp26021
a(S'such problems. This category also includes search algorithms, branch and bound enumeration and backtracking.'
p26022
g19085
tp26023
a(S'Randomized algorithm'
p26024
g19085
tp26025
a(S'Such algorithms make some choices randomly (or pseudo randomly). They can be very useful in finding approximate solutions for problems where finding exact solutions '
p26026
g19085
tp26027
a(S'can be impractical (see heuristic method below). For some of these problems, it is known that the fastest approximations must involve some randomness.[56] Whether '
p26028
g19085
tp26029
a(S'randomized algorithms with polynomial time complexity can be the fastest algorithms for some problems is an open question known as the P versus NP problem. There are '
p26030
g19085
tp26031
a(S'two large classes of such algorithms:'
