a(S'Linear programming'
p26055
g19085
tp26056
a(S'When searching for optimal solutions to a linear function bound to linear equality and inequality constraints, the constraints of the problem can be used directly in '
p26057
g19085
tp26058
a(S'producing the optimal solutions. There are algorithms that can solve any problem in this category, such as the popular simplex algorithm.[57] Problems that can be solved '
p26059
g19085
tp26060
a(S'with linear programming include the maximum flow problem for directed graphs. If a problem additionally requires that one or more of the unknowns must be an integer '
p26061
g19085
tp26062
a(S'then it is classified in integer programming. A linear programming algorithm can solve such a problem if it can be proved that all restrictions for integer values are '
p26063
g19085
tp26064
a(S'superficial, i.e., the solutions satisfy these restrictions anyway. In the general case, a specialized algorithm or an algorithm that finds approximate solutions is used, '
p26065
g19085
tp26066
a(S'depending on the difficulty of the problem.'
