a(S'The greedy method'
p26087
g19085
tp26088
a(S'A greedy algorithm is similar to a dynamic programming algorithm in that it works by examining substructures, in this case not of the problem but of a given solution. Such '
p26089
g19085
tp26090
a(S'algorithms start with some solution, which may be given or have been constructed in some way, and improve it by making small modifications. For some problems they '
p26091
g19085
tp26092
a(S'can find the optimal solution while for others they stop at local optima, that is, at solutions that cannot be improved by the algorithm but are not optimum. The most popular '
p26093
g19085
tp26094
a(S'use of greedy algorithms is for finding the minimal spanning tree where finding the optimal solution is possible with this method. Huffman Tree, Kruskal, Prim, Sollin are '
p26095
g19085
tp26096
a(S'greedy algorithms that can solve this optimization problem.'
p26097
g19085
tp26098
a(S'The heuristic method'
p26099
g19085
tp26100
a(S'In optimization problems, heuristic algorithms can be used to find a solution close to the optimal solution in cases where finding the optimal solution is impractical. These '
p26101
g19085
tp26102
a(S'algorithms work by getting closer and closer to the optimal solution as they progress. In principle, if run for an infinite amount of time, they will find the optimal solution. '
p26103
g19085
tp26104
a(S'Their merit is that they can find a solution very close to the optimal solution in a relatively short time. Such algorithms include local search, tabu search, simulated '
p26105
g19085
tp26106
a(S'annealing, and genetic algorithms. Some of them, like simulated annealing, are non deterministic algorithms while others, like tabu search, are deterministic. When a '
p26107
g19085
tp26108
a(S'bound on the error of the non optimal solution is known, the algorithm is further categorized as an approximation algorithm.'
